From jack wood Subject BBB Autoline Arbitration My BBB Autoline arbitration experience is The outcome was decidedly I won the battle but lost the The arbitrator found that the car was defective but decided to offer a repurchase well below market value At the time of the hearing average retail on my truck in the NADA book was but the decision was for I wrote a letter to the Council of Better Business Bureaus pointing out the fact that if you have an automobile that does not depreciate rapidly the manufacturer has no incentive to deal with There is no way that the manufacturer can loose because they can turn around and sell the vehicle at a profit if the consumer is awarded a The attitude of Chevrolet's representative at the hearing tends to support this point of view he was totally unprepared and did not seem to take the proceeding very I decided to take the repurchase even though I am getting totally screwed on the I will not have to deal with continuing repairs or selling a lemon myself and I have no case for a civil suit based on the Idaho lemon I am planning to send a letter to my elected representatives telling them how utterly ridiculous the Idaho lemon law The law allows for a use deduction equal to the IRS mileage As if Chevrolet were buying my gas and paying for my Summary of the case In May I bought a new ton HD Chevrolet Between May and December this vehicle required repair after Systems that required attention included the transmission heater fan paint suspension and The main problem was the five speed manual They could not install a non defective transmission in at least four So in summary it is possible to get a repurchase but you are going to get screwed on the price unless you paid too much in the first place or if your car happens to be a model that depreciates